THE HOUR OF PRAYER. P. M.
B
6
8
9
582
PRAYER AND PRAISE.
"Enter into thy closet."
H
to
My God! is an-y hour so sweet, From blush of morn to evening star, As that which calls me to thy feet, The hour of prayer.
à
H
№
Blest is the tranquil hour of morn, And blest that solemn hour of eve, When on the wings of prayer upborne, The world I leave.
194
Charlotte Elliott.
2 For then a dayspring shines on me,
Brighter than moon's ethereal glow;
And richer dews descend from thee
Than earth can know.
4
94
Then is my strength by thee renewed ;
Then are my sins by thee forgiven,
Then dost thou cheer my solitude
With hopes of heaven.
WHAT A FRIEND, 8s & 7s. D. "Cast all your care upon him."
What a friend we have in Jesus, All our sins and griefs to bear!
E
Fine.
3 No words can tell what sweet relief
Here for my every want I find;
What strength for warfare, balm for grief
What peace of mind!
Lord! till I reach yon blissful shore,
No privilege so dear shall be
As thus my inmost soul to pour
In prayer to thee.
D
195
Anon.
2 Have we trials and temptations ?
Is there trouble anywhere?
We should never be discouraged,
Take it to the Lord in prayer.
Can we find a Friend so faithful,
Who will all our sorrows share?
Jesus knows our every weakness,
Take it to the Lord in prayer.
E. MAUDE CLINE.
Ev'ry thing to God in pray'r! 0, what peace we often for feit,
Ev'ry thing to God in pray'r!
-
S.

0, what needless pain we bear,
3 Are we weak and heavy laden,
Cumbered with a load of care?
Precious Savior, still our refuge,—
Take it to the Lord in prayer.
Do thy friends despise, forsake thee?
Take it to the Lord in prayer;
In his arms he'll take and shield thee;
Thou wilt find a solace there.
